{{pp|small=yes}} {{Infobox member of the Knesset |image = |birth_date = 2 March 1921 |birth_place = [[Kingdom of Romania|Romania]] |Year of Aliyah = 1949 |death_date = {{Death date and age|2000|6|26|1921|3|2|df=y}} |death_place = |Knesset(s) = [[Israeli legislative election, 1981|10]], [[Israeli legislative election, 1984|11]], [[Israeli legislative election, 1992|13]] |party1 = [[Agudat Yisrael]] |partyyears1 = 1981–1988 |party2 = [[United Torah Judaism]] |partyyears2 = 1992–1996 |party3 = [[Agudat Yisrael]] |partyyears3 = 1996 }}
'''Avraham Yosef Shapira''' ({{lang-he|אברהם יוסף שפירא}}; born 2 March 1921, died 26 June 2000) was an [[Israel]]i politician and businessman.
==Biography== Born in Romania in 1921, Shapira attended the Kokhav MeYa'akov [[yeshiva]] in [[Trzebinia]], and was later certified as a teacher. He made [[aliyah]] to Israel in 1949. He began working with his father, a furrier. In 1959 he bought a carpet factory, Carmel Carpets, in [[Or Akiva]]. At its peak the business employed 1,600 employees and had an annual turnover of $500 million.<ref name=G>[https://www.theguardian.com/news/2000/jul/04/guardianobituaries.israel Avraham Shapira: Religious powerbroker of Israel's turbulent politics] The Guardian, 4 July 2000</ref>
He joined [[Agudat Yisrael]], and became chairman of its [[Tel Aviv]] branch. He was elected to the Knesset on the party's list in [[Israeli legislative election, 1981|1981]] and became chairman of the governing coalition. He was re-elected in [[Israeli legislative election, 1984|1984]], after which he chaired the Finance Committee. He also served as chairman of the [[Bank of Israel]]'s steering committee,<ref>[https://www.knesset.gov.il/mk/eng/mk_eng.asp?mk_individual_id_t=177 Avraham Yosef Schapira: Public Activities] Knesset website</ref> wielding a strong influence on the country's financial state.
He lost his seat in the [[Israeli legislative election, 1988|1988 elections]], but returned to the Knesset in [[Israeli legislative election, 1992|1992]] (by which time the party had formed the United Torah Judaism alliance with [[Degel HaTorah]]). He lost his seat again in the [[Israeli legislative election, 1996|1996 elections]].
He died in 2000 at the age of 79.
