'''Border effects''' refer to asymmetries in trade patterns between cities and regions of different countries that share a national border and those that are located in the same country. Usually, trade volume is much lesser between the former cities and regions.<ref>[http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/cross_fac/iatl/reinvention/issues/volume6issue2/vanagas/ Border Effects Among EU Countries: Do National Identity and Cultural Differences Matter?]</ref> Economic integration (as in the EU) may be a solution to overcome these effects.

